05503nam a22007455i 9780812290059DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20132009pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013956159  a97808122900597 a10.9783/97808122900592doi  a(DE-B1597)449798  a(OCoLC)922662310  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aREL0150002bisacsh04a274/.051 aVan Engen, John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSisters and Brothers of the Common Life :bThe Devotio Moderna and the World of the Later Middle Ages /cJohn Van Engen. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2013] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (448 p.) :b19 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Middle Ages Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tIntroduction: The Devotio Moderna and Modern History -- tChapter one. Converts in the Middle Ages -- tChapter two. Modern-Day Converts in the Low Countries -- tChapter three. Suspicion and Inquisition -- tChapter four. From Converts to Communities: Tertiaries, Sisters, Brothers, Schoolboys, Canons -- tChapter five. Inventing a Communal Household: Goods, Customs, Labor, and ‘‘Republican’’ Harmony -- tChapter six. Defending the Modern-Day Devout: Public Expansion Under Scrutiny -- tChapter seven. Proposing a Theological Rationale: The Freedom of the ‘‘Christian Religion’’ -- tChapter eight. Taking the Spiritual Offensive: Caring for the Self, Examining the Soul, Progressing in Virtue -- tConclusion: Private Gatherings and Self-Made Societies in the Fifteenth Century -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Devotio Moderna, or Modern Devout, puzzled their contemporaries. Beginning in the 1380s in market towns along the Ijssel River of the east-central Netherlands and in the county of Holland, they formed households organized as communes and forged lives centered on private devotion. They lived on city streets alongside their neighbors, managed properties and rents in common, and worked in the textile and book trades, all the while refusing to profess vows as members of any religious order or to acquire spouses and personal property as lay citizens. They defended their self-designed style of life as exemplary and sustained it in the face of opposition, their women labeled "beguines" and their men "lollards," both meant as derogatory terms. Yet the movement grew, drawing in women and schoolboys, priests and laymen, and spreading outward toward Münster, Flanders, and Cologne.The Devout were arguably more culturally significant than the Lollards and Beguines, yet they have commanded far less scholarly attention in English. John Van Engen's magisterial book keeps the Modern Devout at its center and thinks through their story anew. Few interpreters have read the Devout so insistently within their own time and space by looking to the social and religious conditions that marked towns and parishes in northern Europe during the fifteenth century and examining the widespread upheavals in cultural and religious life between the 1370s and the 1440s. In Sisters and Brothers of the Common Life, Van Engen grasps the Devout in their humanity, communities, and beliefs, and places them firmly within the urban societies of the Low Countries and the cultures we call late medieval.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 4aReligious Studies. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / History.2bisacsh  aMedieval and Renaissance Studies.  aReligion.  aReligious Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Pack